<ul id="commtree_64569529"><li id="tree_64569697" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64569697" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64569697" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64569697" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64569697" name="comment_link_64569697" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23364269&amp;cid=64569697" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64569697)" >Re:Venn Diagram HIV/Covid</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64569697" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64569697); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~wickerprints">wickerprints</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~wickerprints">( 1094741 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64569697">		
		on Saturday June 22, 2024 @05:30PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23364269&amp;cid=64569697">#64569697</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64569697"><p>"Sizeable minority" means what, exactly?  Cite a study that estimates the incidence of such individuals.</p><p>In any group of sufficient size, there are always some who do not engage in best practices, but it is very often the case that these examples are brought up only when the group is marginalized, in order to paint all of them with that broad brush.  If American attitudes about the COVID-19 pandemic has proven anything, people in general do many, many things that are not conducive to their health and threaten the public health of others, yet it's not trotted out as an example of how all straight people have a respiratory disease fetish.</p><p>The notion that HIV is more prevalent among gay men because of the existence of "bug chasers" is not only bigoted, but in open contradiction to historical fact.  "Bug chasing"--however common or uncommon it may be--did not even exist as a phenomenon when the AIDS epidemic was decimating the gay male community in the 80s.  The overwhelming attitude was that of extreme anxiety, panic, and fear, because prior to the identification of the viral vector and the availability of antigen testing, nobody knew if they were positive but presymptomatic.  In those days, men would appear to suddenly fall ill as their immune systems collapsed and opportunistic infections started to destroy entire organ systems.  That said, there were some people who, in response to the unbearable stress and uncertainty of the situation and lack of treatment options, compounded by government inaction that suggested a deliberate policy to leverage HIV as a way to let gay men die, on top of the longstanding discrimination and bigotry against LGBT people, rather fatalistically thought they should just "get it over with" and let themselves get infected, because at least they would no longer need to worry if they would survive.  And that was NOT "bug chasing."  That was a very human reaction to a situation in which many men felt that they were walking around with a metaphorical time bomb strapped to their chest that might explode at any moment.  Due to the discrimination at the time, very little historical data has survived that documents how common this fatalism was.</p><p>The so called fetishization of seroconversion--"bug chasing"--is only something that began much later, well after AIDS killed a generation of urban gay men, because once researchers established that AIDS was caused by HIV, and that it was transmitted through the transfer of blood or semen via unprotected sex, condom use among gay men skyrocketed.  There was a time when condoms were everywhere--in bars, convenience store counters, doctor's offices, cafes--they were offered up like candy, and there were such things as "condom lollipops."  This was before HAART and PrEP:  there were early-generation antivirals to delay the progression of HIV to AIDS, but they were extremely toxic.  So condom use was the gold standard for prevention.  And it was because of this extensive use of condoms that some men started to rebel against it.  They felt that fluid exchange was an important part of the intimacy of sex.  The point I'm making here is that "bug chasing" was in part born out of a response to the only preventative option that gay men at the time were offered, and that this could not have happened before HIV became endemic in the gay male community, therefore disproving your assertion that HIV infection is driven by a "fetish" for being infected.</p><p>Now that PrEP exists, condom use among gay men has fallen significantly; however, other STIs have become more common.  Is this a "smart" thing to do?  Is it in their best public health interest?  Of course not.  But do we judge that any more harshly or with more bigotry than we judge obese diabetics who continue to make poor dietary choices?  Do we extrapolate and stereotype every gay man and assert they must be "bug chasers" even when they use condoms and are also on PrEP?  That's where your bigotry shows.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64569697">
